Prologue
“Please!” Queen Elwin pleaded, “Don’t send her away! She’s just a child!” The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with the royal advisor standing by. The queen had given birth to a girl. Just thinking about it, the Ice King couldn’t help but furrow his brow.
The infant looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, with a few strands of blue hair. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, before this, he only had a son.
“You have only two choices: either kill this child or leave her in the wilderness. Elwin, this is your punishment.” He spat out her name hatefully, as if it were poison. He always did this.
The Frostland Kingdom was not always a kingdom. It once split into two parts, north and south. The north established a non-magical kingdom, while the south was a kingdom full of magical powers. Due to the greed of the north, the two kingdoms waged endless wars until the south proposed a truce.
The Southern kingdom was already in despair, and the royal family was willing to do anything to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed to marry their only princess to the North, making her the Queen of the North and bearing a son who would become the future king. After that, the South would merge with the North to establish a unified kingdom. The North accepted this proposal, and Princess Elwin was thus married to Prince Akur.
"Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me—lock me up, exile me, even kill me," Queen Elwin pleaded, hugging her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at the queen, his eyes filled with contempt. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would show her a little mercy. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him during his darkest times, and gave him children.
"Very well. The child can stay in the palace," said the Ice King. Hearing this, Queen Elwin let out a sigh of relief. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisors and Queen Elwin both showed horrified expressions. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "As you command, my king," she bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take the queen's daughter to an empty room belonging to Elwin. After that, he ordered the guards to bring Elwin to the execution field where all citizens could see.
As the guards led her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen — also the kindest queen — about to be executed, and they became extremely angry. Some cried, some shouted and tried to attack the guards, and others wondered why such a thing was happening; but they all had the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they treating her like this?"
When Elwin approached the wooden stake, the most terrifying person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of the fire刑. The former queen Elwin was to be burned alive. No one should be subjected to fire刑, even criminals. In the Frostland Kingdom, fire刑 was the most cruel punishment.
Elwin was tied to a wooden post, and the king began telling how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostland Kingdom refused to believe, and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the wooden post, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Carly, live!" The life of Queen Elwin came to an end.
The hall was silent.
In the southern wing of this cold palace, a constant "tapping" sound echoed from the leftmost room. Past servants were always curious about what was inside the room, yet too afraid to get close. The maids moved around the hall, whispering and spreading various rumors. Some believed that the late wife of the Ice King, Elwin, lived in this room, waiting to be released.
They were completely wrong. Avery thought as she walked toward the southern wing, the servants walked along the walls, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there were also many rumors about him, because he was the only one allowed to enter the room.
He knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you in there?" Avery whispered to this complex door, decorated with snowflakes and crowns, symbols of the royal family.
He didn't know whether she would really let him in this time, which was different from before. I still have the bruise from last time. Avery recalled this incident and couldn't help but smile. At that time, Carly threw a book at him, but immediately apologized when she saw who it was.
A sound came from the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere, just stayed there.
"May I come in?" Avery asked, unable to forget the consequences of entering without permission last time.
The room once again echoed with a soft sound. It seemed to be saying, "Come in." Avery felt a chill, unsure whether it was from the cold or from that voice. Although he had been there for many years, hearing the sound coming from the room still made him feel a bit strange.
"I'm coming in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. By normal standards, the scene inside the room was very unusual, but this was also expected. The room was filled with paper. Books were scattered around, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures in the room. There were no windows, and there was almost no light. This place was also colder than other parts of the palace (which explained a lot). The room looked as if it had been attacked by a blizzard, with everything in disarray.
The girl in the room was curled up in bed, wrapped in a blanket, reading a notebook. A small lantern lit up the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Avery asked as he sat by Carly's bed.
